✅ GitHub Contribution Report

Task: Fork, Pull, Commit, and Push Workflow
Objective:
To successfully contribute to an open-source project or a shared repository by using GitHub’s collaborative workflow: Fork → Clone → Commit → Push → Pull Request.

🔁 1. Fork the Repository

Action:
Navigated to the target repository on GitHub and clicked "Fork" to create a personal copy under my own GitHub account.
Result:
A new forked repository appeared at:
https://github.com/my-username/repo-name
📥 2. Clone the Repository

Command:
git clone https://github.com/my-username/repo-name.git
cd repo-name
Purpose:
This created a local copy of the forked repo to work on changes.
🔧 3. Make Changes Locally

Edited source files (e.g., fixed a bug, added a feature, or improved documentation).
Verified changes with:
git status
git diff
💾 4. Commit the Changes

Command:
git add .
git commit -m "Fix: corrected typo in README and updated usage example"
Result:
A clean, descriptive commit was created with all intended changes.
📤 5. Push to Forked Repository

Command:
git push origin main
Note:
If working on a branch:
git push origin my-feature-branch
📬 6. Create a Pull Request (PR)

Navigated to the original repo on GitHub.
Clicked "Compare & Pull Request".
Wrote a clear title and description of the changes.
Submitted the PR for review.

